INSERT INTO `Cases` VALUES (2,1,'Case 12','On March 8th, you examine a 5-year-old bay Standardbred gelding with a nose bleed.He raced 4 days ago and developed a slight bloody nose during the race. The epistaxis seemed to abate after the race. The horse seemed normal the day after the race. However, the epistaxis recurred 2 days after racing. The horse subsequently developed anorexia, a fever, and a cough. The fever seemed to decrease after the trainer administered Tribressen to the horse but the epistaxis and cough have persisted. The last dose of Tribressen was 24 hours ago.','vaulter82@gmail.com'),(3,2,'Case 2 - Advanced Equine Internal Medicine','<p>On July 3, a 7-year-old chestnut American Saddlebred mare has been referred to your equine practice by a local mixed practitioner. The mare arrived in your area (Barrington) on June 26 from central Kentucky where she had been verbally sold for $40,000. The day after her arrival, the mare did not eat anything and had a temperature of 103.5F.</p>','kedwards@illinois.edu'),(4,3,'Case 3 - 6-year old Standardbred Pacing Mare','<p>On June 7, a 6-year-old Standardbred pacing mare has developed mild signs of colic. This is the fourth time in the last 6 months that she has colicked. The tramer called you today because even though you are notoriously expensive, you have the reputation of fixing difficult and complicated cases like this one. The trainer reports that m the past, the mare has always responded quickly to mineral oil, Banamine or phenylbutazone, and stall rest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The mare is housed at the racetrack with 19 other horses in this trainer&#39;s stable. This trainer has a tendency to want to do much of his own veterinary care such as deworming and other oral therapies including antibiotics and analgesics. He has not to your knowledge used any injectable medications at the track as his best friend and fellow trainer, Mr. I-Can-Make-Em-All-Go-Fast was recently suspended for 30 days for having injectable medications and syringes in the trunk of his car.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The mare and the trainer&#39;s other horses are all fed straight oats and good quality alfalfa hay (you have seen it yourself) and have access to salt blocks in their stalls. This mare has been slightly off feed for 2 days so the trainer has jogged her lightly those days. She has not been racing well for the last 4 starts over the last 2 months. She seems to get to the pole fine but then seems to quit pretty badly. The trainer reports that she has lost 200 pounds in the last 2 months.</p>','noliver@illinois.edu'),(5,4,'Case 4 - 14-year-old bay Quarter Horse gelding','<p>On July 30, you examine a 14-ycar-old bay Quarter Horse gelding with a history of&nbsp;frequent urinations. This urinary behavior has been gomg on stince early April. The&nbsp;<br />\r\nproblem has not gotten worse since it started. The horse still drinks well but the owners are unable to tell you that he is drinking more or less than usual because they have&nbsp;<br />\r\nautomatic waterers in their barn. The horse&#39;s appetite and weight still seem to be normal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The owners have had the horse 3 years. He had a single bout of colic 8 months ago but no apparent colic problems since then. The horse has not been vaccinated for anything since the owners have had him. The horse is tube wormed once yearly (whether he needs it or not) and was last dewormed 1 month ago. The horse is fed half a coffee can of oats once daily and 1 flake of alfalfa hay twice daily. He has access to a large mixed mineral block in his paddock and is often seen to be licking and occasionally eating the salt. He had a negative Coggins test 4-5 years ago. He is used as a pleasure riding horse.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The owners are willing to do anything for the horse if he has a treatable disease but&nbsp;do not want to spend tons of money on a horse that is going to have chronic. incurable problems. Please be somewhat monetarily judicious in your ordering of diagnostic tests for this horse. Below on this page, create a problem list and a list of differentials for each problem. On the following pages (checklists), check your choices in order to create diagnostic and therapeutic plans.&nbsp;</p>','noliver@illinois.edu'),(6,8,'Case #10 - Coughing American Saddlebred Gelding','On June 30th, you are asked to examine an 18-year-old actively showing chestnut American Saddlebred gelding with a 1 month history of mild coughing. Also, approximately 1 month ago, the client noticed a small amount of blood dripping from the left nostril.&nbsp; The horse has been in its present barn since March this year.&nbsp; Previously, the horse was housed for several years in a stall at another barn which closed recently to make way for a housing development.&nbsp; The owner feels that the new barn is excessively dusty and that some other horses in the barn cough excessively.&nbsp; Five years ago the horse had a fairly severe bout of pneumonia.','kedwards@illinois.edu'),(8,8,'Case 10 - Coughing American Saddlebred','On June 30, you are asked to examine an 18-year-old actively-showing chestnut American Saddlebred gelding with a 1 month history of mild coughing.&nbsp; MORE to COME','kedwards@illinois.edu'),(9,10,'Case 1 - Choking Thoroughbred Racing Filly','<p>On April 3rd, a 3-year-old Thoroughbred racing filly has been referred to your hospital with a history of having been choked on March 14, 20, and 26.&nbsp; Since March 26th, she has been fed pellets only with no hay and has been bedded on peat moss.&nbsp; On March 31st, she spiked a temperature and was treated with various antibiotics by the referring veterinarian until she arrived at your hospital.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This filly is owned in partnership by two people.&nbsp; The half owned by the client in whose name the record was completed is insured for $200,000.</p>','kedwards@illinois.edu'),(10,11,'Case 8 - 3-year-old Appaloosa Gelding With Colic','<p>On August 8, you are asked to examine a 3-year-old Appaloosa gelding for colic of 2 days&#39; duration.&nbsp; Four days ago, the horse was dewormed with ivermectin.&nbsp; Two days ago, the horse lay down and acted uncomfortable.&nbsp; He was not observed to pass feces that day.&nbsp; The client administered 10 ml of dipyrone IM and the horse seemed fairly normal for the rest of the night.&nbsp; Another veterinarian examined the horse yesterday, and administered 10 ml of Banamine BID IM and tubed the horse with 1 gallon of mineral oil.&nbsp; On the night of admission, the horse was rolling again and the clients called you to examine him.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You hospitalize the horse and observe him for the remainder of the evening.</p>','kedwards@illinois.edu');
