INSERT INTO `Days` VALUES (2,2,'Day 1'),(3,3,''),(8,3,'<p>No new information provided.</p>'),(9,3,'<p>The mare seemed much improved yesterday.&nbsp; Today she is better than on the day of admission but is not as good as yesterday. She did not eat as well today as yesterday.&nbsp; Since last night, she has eaten half of her oats and about one-third of her hay.&nbsp; She has also drunk approximately 4 gallons of water overnight.&nbsp; There is one new diarrhea spot on the wall but no other evidence of diarrhea.&nbsp; There are some partially formed feces in the stall.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She has received XXXXXXX and oral fluids by nasogastric tube since admission.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The mare is improved but still not normal.</p>'),(10,3,'SOAP:&nbsp; No change.'),(11,4,'<p>The mare was lying down when you entered the stall and seemed reluctant to get up without considerable urging (no, a cattle prod was not necessary). She appears to be thinner than one would expect even for a mare in active race training but she is certainly not emaciated.</p>'),(12,3,'<p>SOAP:&nbsp; No change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have not yet determined a definitive diagnosis and prognosis including the possible reversibility of the disease process, request any further definitive diagnostic tests you wish to request to arrive at a diagnosis.&nbsp; Are there any tests which you have not yet requested which might help you determine the reversibility of the horse&#39;s clinical condition?</p>'),(13,5,'On physical examination, the horse&#39;s attitude is bright. alert, and responsive. His temperature, heart rate, and respiratory rate are 99.0 F, 32/min, and 12/min, respectively. He is overweight if &nbsp;anything. There are brownish discolored areas on the white socks of his hind legs. You observe him to stretch to urinate about every 30 minutes and when he does so, he produces small amounts of dark yellow-to-brown urine. The prepuce seems to be somewhat swollen also.');
